            <h2 style="text-align:left;">History</h2>
            <p style="text-align:left;" class="lead">
                Against the backdrop of drastic budget cuts at the federal level since 2017, immigrant and refugee communities, as well as many low-income families,
                have been gradually turned away from various social services that have helped their successful integration to the American society for the past two
                generations. Unfortunately, Jacksonville and Northeast Florida have been no exception to this growing challenge. The lack of access to adequate services
                reportedly led to a number of newcomers and low-income households falling victim to scams and unethical business practices over the years.
            </p>
            <p style="text-align:left;" class="lead">
                In April 2019, Christine Rothberg and Basma Alawee met at a regular Refugee Taskforce Meeting and began compiling a list of trusted and welcoming resources
                in the local area to address the challenge. The initial idea was to draft up a list that fits on a single-page document; over the next few months, however,
                more volunteers joined the effort and the list quickly expanded. Eventually, a group of students from the University of North Florida (UNF) volunteered to
                turn the list into an online database that can be visualized on a publicly accessible map for easy use. In January 2020, WeaveTales was officially appointed
                to manage, maintain, and update the database. Since then, WeaveTales has worked with UNF students to improve the system ahead of the official launch and continues to manage the website.
            </p>
            <p style="text-align:left;" class="lead">
                To learn more about WeaveTales, the managing entity of Neighborly, click <a href="https://weavetales.org/what-we-do" target="_blank">here</a>.
            </p>

